====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# To confine in, or as in, a pound; to [[impound]].
#* {{c.|1620}} anonymous, “{{w|Tom o' Bedlam|Tom o’ Bedlam’s Song}}” in ''Giles Earle his Booke'' (British Museum, Additional MSS. 24, 665):
#*: When I short haue shorne my sowce face<br>& swigg’d my horny barrell,<br>In an oaken Inne I '''pound''' my skin<br>as a suite of guilt apparrell
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1644|author={{w|John Milton}}|title={{w|Areopagitica}}; A speech of Mr. John Milton for the Liberty of Unlicenc’d Printing, to the Parlament of England|passage=And he who were pleasantly disposed, could not well avoid to liken it to the exploit of that gallant man, who thought to '''pound''' up the crows by shutting his park gate.}}

===Etymology 3===
From an alteration of earlier {{m|en|poun}}, {{m|en|pown}}, from {{inh|en|enm|pounen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|pūnian||to pound, beat, bray, bruise, crush}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*pūn-|t=broken pieces, rubble}}. Related to {{cog|stq|Pün|t=debris, fragments}}, {{cog|fy|pún|t=debris, rubble}}, {{cog|nl|puin||debris, fragments, rubbish}}, {{cog|nds|pun||fragments}}. 

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|poun}}, {{l|en|pown}} {{qualifier|obsolete or dialectal}}

